<div class="col" style="background:#ced9fb>
<h2>Armed Syrian Mobs Patrolling Turkish Towns</h2>
<p>When the Turkish security guards (bekçi) stopped and searched a young Syrian man late at midnight, they discovered a 60cm long sharp metal object carefully hidden inside his belt. The man, whose behaviour raised suspicion, was asked to show his ID. It was confirmed that the young man's name was Mahmud H. and he was from Syria. Upon searching the man, the night shift security officers thought that the man's belt looked very odd and he was acting strangely. Soon, they discovered the sharp metal object which looked like a sabre with a thin sharp spine designed to be worn as a belt around the waist.</p><br/>

<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><object class="BLOG_video_class" contentid="935d7ba3399bbf67" height="266" id="BLOG_video-935d7ba3399bbf67" width="320"></object></div>

<p><h2>Syrian Sabres Were First Seen Back in 2018:</h2></p>

<p>The Syrian sabre is a popular combat weapon amongst foreign nationals who use social platforms to share videos and images of themselves with such weapons. Back in 2018, 3 Syrian nationals had been arrested after an armed robbery attempt to a family home at Osmangazi, Bursa. The family members had described the armed Syrians as being very dangerous with hidden sabres in their belts. The 3 Syrians had stolen 3 mobile phones and ₺500 from the family. Later, the 3 Syrians whose names have never been shared with the public, was found with stolen items and sabres.</p>

<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjd4NO3ZJ7UwjKYVkjTrP8OrcXIuJ2veeyXPY-JhE7bLFzZpmIrPDlnXtvrRfoPsL0gpDb_auKHyrMLYI-VGyGHeYJSSITENs_b7GDMs2muZ_eF6OljgxFyk4RvIMhZzjkcGCGMWsL7qOSjCOcrxw-Lwfa6x3DtDsSo4U4DmALfOo_BtTDk8LvaJhup/s560/syriansabre.jpg" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" data-original-height="560" data-original-width="532" height="400" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjd4NO3ZJ7UwjKYVkjTrP8OrcXIuJ2veeyXPY-JhE7bLFzZpmIrPDlnXtvrRfoPsL0gpDb_auKHyrMLYI-VGyGHeYJSSITENs_b7GDMs2muZ_eF6OljgxFyk4RvIMhZzjkcGCGMWsL7qOSjCOcrxw-Lwfa6x3DtDsSo4U4DmALfOo_BtTDk8LvaJhup/w380-h400/syriansabre.jpg" width="380" /></a></div>

<p>The armed Syrians mobs, who carry sabres, knives, batons and pistols usually terrorise the cities after dark. The police and late night security guards cannot always provide safety for the locals </p><p></p><div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><object class="BLOG_video_class" contentid="ca4fe0d59837d96e" height="266" id="BLOG_video-ca4fe0d59837d96e" width="320"></object></div><div style="text-align: center;">Syrian mobs in Adana, Turkey</div> <p></p></div><div class="column" style="background-color: white;"><br /></div></div></div>

